T1  - Are fund managers rewarded for taking cyclical risks?
AU  - Ryan, Ellen
JO  - Journal of Financial Markets
VL  - 68
SP  - 100893
PY  - 2024
DA  - 2024/03/01/
SN  - 1386-4181
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/j.finmar.2024.100893
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1386418124000119
KW  - Financial stability
KW  - Investment funds
KW  - Incentive
KW  - Risk-taking
KW  - Macroprudential policy
AB  - The investment fund sector has expanded dramatically since 2008, increasing the capacity for its risk-taking to generate negative spillovers. This paper provides empirical evidence for the existence of wide-spread risk-taking incentives in the investment fund sector, with a particular focus on incentives for synchronized, cyclical risk-taking which could have systemic risk implications. Incentives arise from the positive response of investors to returns achieved through cyclical risk-taking and non-linearities in the relationship between fund returns and fund flows. The fact that market discipline may not be sufficient to ensure prudent behavior among managers creates a clear case for macroprudential regulatory intervention.
